<subSubSection id="11E3DCD4FFB6FFDAFCEEFEB1FA6EFE55" pageId="9" pageNumber="278" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="59468F5FFFB6FFDAFCEEFEB1FA6EFE55" blockId="9.[801,1454,279,463]" pageId="9" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis id="6B8D534DFFB6FFDAFCEEFEB1FA4FFEB5" box="[839,1423,279,303]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="278">
Distribution and ecology. – 
<taxonomicName id="9EF9F4DCFFB6FFDAFB2AFEB1FA4FFEB5" authorityName="Buerki, Callm., Munzinger &amp; Lowry" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Buerki, Callm., Munzinger &amp; Lowry" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[1155,1423,279,303]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Lepidocupania" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="9" pageNumber="278" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oedipoda">Lepidocupania oedipoda</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is restricted to Grande Terre, extending to the northwest in the Belep archipelago (Art Island); it grows in maquis vegetation, humid forests, gallery forests, and forest remnants, often along streams, usually on hills or mountainsides, on serpentine, greywacke and schist, from sea level to 
<quantity id="9E0122BAFFB6FFDAFB69FE11FAC1FE54" box="[1216,1281,439,463]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="278" unit="m" value="850.0">850 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation id="3D68F2AEFFB6FFDAFAB8FE11FA63FE55" author="ADEMA, F." box="[1297,1443,439,463]" pageId="9" pageNumber="278" refId="ref11451" refString="ADEMA, F. (1991). Cupaniopsis Radlk. (Sapindaceae): a monograph. Leiden Bot. Ser. 15." type="book" year="1991">ADEMA, 1991</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
